<Layout title="Fertility Preservation">
	<section class="page-header">
		<div class="container">
			<h1>Fertility Preservation</h1>
			<p>Freezing eggs, sperm, or embryos to protect future fertility options.</p>
		</div>
	</section>

	<section class="content-container">
		<h2>Overview</h2>
		<p>Fertility preservation allows you to freeze reproductive cells for future use. This can be for medical reasons (before cancer treatment) or elective reasons (delaying parenthood). Modern vitrification techniques have dramatically improved survival rates for frozen eggs and embryos.</p>

		<h2>Egg Freezing (Oocyte Cryopreservation)</h2>

		<h3>Who Should Consider Egg Freezing</h3>
		<ul>
			<li><strong>Medical reasons:</strong> Before chemotherapy, radiation, or other gonadotoxic treatments</li>
			<li><strong>Elective reasons:</strong> Delaying parenthood for career, education, or personal reasons</li>
			<li><strong>Gender transition:</strong> Before hormone therapy</li>
			<li><strong>Family history:</strong> Of early menopause</li>
			<li><strong>Endometriosis:</strong> Which can damage ovarian reserve over time</li>
		</ul>

		<h3>When to Freeze</h3>
		<div class="info-box">
			<strong>Age matters significantly:</strong> Egg quality declines with age. For best outcomes, freeze before age 35-36. Freezing after 38 results in lower success rates per egg.
		</div>

		<table>
			<thead>
				<tr>
					<th>Age at Freezing</th>
					<th>Eggs Typically Retrieved</th>
					<th>Eggs Needed for ~1 Baby</th>
					<th>Estimated Success Rate</th>
				</tr>
			</thead>
			<tbody>
				<tr>
					<td>&lt;35</td>
					<td>10-20</td>
					<td>10-15 eggs</td>
					<td>70-80% per batch</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td>35-37</td>
					<td>8-15</td>
					<td>15-20 eggs</td>
					<td>50-60% per batch</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td>38-40</td>
					<td>5-10</td>
					<td>20-30 eggs</td>
					<td>30-40% per batch</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td>&gt;40</td>
					<td>3-8</td>
					<td>30+ eggs</td>
					<td>15-25% per batch</td>
				</tr>
			</tbody>
		</table>
		<p><em>Note: Multiple cycles may be needed to bank sufficient eggs.</em></p>

		<h3>The Process</h3>
		<ol>
			<li><strong>Initial consultation and testing:</strong> AMH, antral follicle count, general health</li>
			<li><strong>Ovarian stimulation:</strong> 10-14 days of hormone injections</li>
			<li><strong>Monitoring:</strong> Ultrasounds and bloodwork every 2-3 days</li>
			<li><strong>Trigger shot:</strong> 36 hours before retrieval</li>
			<li><strong>Egg retrieval:</strong> Outpatient procedure under sedation</li>
			<li><strong>Vitrification:</strong> Eggs flash-frozen and stored in liquid nitrogen</li>
		</ol>

		<h3>Costs</h3>
		<table>
			<tbody>
				<tr>
					<td>Egg freezing cycle</td>
					<td>$6,000-$12,000</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td>Medications</td>
					<td>$3,000-$6,000</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td>Anesthesia</td>
					<td>$500-$1,000</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td>Annual storage</td>
					<td>$500-$1,000/year</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td><strong>Total per cycle</strong></td>
					<td><strong>$10,000-$18,000</strong></td>
				</tr>
			</tbody>
		</table>

		<h3>Future Use</h3>
		<p>When ready to use frozen eggs:</p>
		<ul>
			<li>Eggs are thawed (85-95% survival rate)</li>
			<li>Fertilized with sperm via ICSI</li>
			<li>Embryos cultured and transferred</li>
			<li>Additional cost: $4,000-$8,000 for thaw + transfer cycle</li>
		</ul>

		<h2>Sperm Freezing (Sperm Cryopreservation)</h2>

		<h3>Who Should Consider Sperm Freezing</h3>
		<ul>
			<li><strong>Before cancer treatment:</strong> Chemotherapy, radiation, surgery</li>
			<li><strong>Before vasectomy:</strong> As backup</li>
			<li><strong>Military deployment or work travel</strong></li>
			<li><strong>Gender transition</strong></li>
			<li><strong>Declining sperm quality</strong></li>
			<li><strong>Before high-risk activities</strong></li>
		</ul>

		<h3>The Process</h3>
		<ol>
			<li>Provide sample at clinic or sperm bank</li>
			<li>Sample analyzed for count, motility, morphology</li>
			<li>Sample divided into vials and frozen</li>
			<li>Stored in liquid nitrogen indefinitely</li>
		</ol>

		<h3>Costs</h3>
		<table>
			<tbody>
				<tr>
					<td>Initial freezing and analysis</td>
					<td>$300-$1,000</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td>Annual storage</td>
					<td>$200-$500/year</td>
				</tr>
			</tbody>
		</table>

		<div class="success-box">
			<strong>Good news:</strong> Sperm freezing is simpler and less expensive than egg freezing. Sperm survive freezing well with 50-75% post-thaw survival. One sample can produce multiple vials for multiple attempts.
		</div>

		<h2>Embryo Freezing</h2>

		<h3>Why Freeze Embryos</h3>
		<ul>
			<li><strong>During IVF:</strong> Extra embryos from a cycle</li>
			<li><strong>Before medical treatment:</strong> Higher success rates than egg freezing alone</li>
			<li><strong>For couples:</strong> When both partners' gametes are available</li>
			<li><strong>Genetic testing:</strong> While waiting for PGT results</li>
		</ul>

		<h3>Success Rates</h3>
		<p>Embryo freezing has the highest success rates of all fertility preservation methods:</p>
		<ul>
			<li>95-99% embryo survival after thaw</li>
			<li>Success rates based on age at time of embryo creation</li>
			<li>Same success rates as fresh embryos when thawed</li>
		</ul>

		<h3>Costs</h3>
		<table>
			<tbody>
				<tr>
					<td>IVF cycle (to create embryos)</td>
					<td>$12,000-$17,000</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td>Medications</td>
					<td>$3,000-$6,000</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td>Embryo freezing</td>
					<td>$1,000-$2,000</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td>Annual storage</td>
					<td>$500-$1,000/year</td>
				</tr>
				<tr>
					<td>Future FET cycle</td>
					<td>$3,000-$5,000</td>
				</tr>
			</tbody>
		</table>

		<h2>Ovarian Tissue Freezing</h2>
		<div class="card">
			<h3>Experimental Option</h3>
			<p>Ovarian tissue is surgically removed, frozen, and later re-implanted. This option is:</p>
			<ul>
				<li>Used primarily for prepubescent girls before cancer treatment</li>
				<li>An option when there's no time for egg freezing</li>
				<li>Still considered experimental at some centers</li>
				<li>Has resulted in live births when tissue is reimplanted</li>
			</ul>
		</div>

		<h2>Insurance Coverage</h2>
		<ul>
			<li><strong>Medical fertility preservation:</strong> Many states require coverage before cancer treatment</li>
			<li><strong>Elective freezing:</strong> Rarely covered; some employers offer this benefit</li>
			<li>Check your specific plan details</li>
		</ul>

		<h2>How Long Can Cells Be Stored?</h2>
		<ul>
			<li>Eggs, sperm, and embryos can be stored indefinitely in liquid nitrogen</li>
			<li>Babies have been born from embryos frozen 20+ years</li>
			<li>No evidence of declining quality over time in storage</li>
		</ul>

		<h2>Considerations</h2>

		<div class="warning-box">
			<strong>Important:</strong> Freezing eggs or embryos does not guarantee a future baby. It's best thought of as insurance - improving your chances, but not a certainty.
		</div>

		<h3>Questions to Consider</h3>
		<ul>
			<li>How many eggs/embryos should I bank?</li>
			<li>What happens if I don't use them?</li>
			<li>What's my clinic's thaw survival rate?</li>
			<li>What are the storage costs long-term?</li>
			<li>If freezing embryos: What happens in case of divorce or death?</li>
		</ul>

